## Maintainer verdict

**Do not commit this as the final P3-LR-SYS deliverable yet.** The source set is mostly real and relevant, and the review is substantially decision-oriented, but several load-bearing methodology claims are wrong or overstated. Most importantly, it does not yet resolve how systems with different or missing energy-measurement boundaries can participate in the binding W1 resource frontier.

I found no clearly hallucinated papers among the spot-checked entries. The problem is characterization and overclaiming, not fabricated bibliography.

## Three most important concerns, ranked

1. **The binding energy comparison remains undefined.**  
   SYS concedes that CPU energy is missing and GPU energy is only a component estimate, while Programme-3 requires every W1 system to fit a binding `max energy/query` budget. GPU-only NVML, CPU RAPL, and full-system wall power are not comparable measurement boundaries. A `MISSING` cell is honest reporting, but it does not define frontier admissibility or permit a W1 comparison. P3-D-HW needs an explicit rule: common full-system boundary, a rigorously validated boundary conversion, or energy becomes non-binding on rigs lacking comparable measurements. Until then, [SYS §2/§11](</home/ec2-user/css/kernel/kernel-of-truth/docs/next/lit/SYS.md:144>) has identified the blocker but not de-risked it.

2. **The adopted workload protocol misreads MLPerf and coordinated omission.**  
   MLPerf SingleStream and MultiStream are closed-loop: the next query is issued after completion. Only Server uses scheduled Poisson arrivals. The review nevertheless says MLPerf embodies open-loop discipline, prohibits closed-loop drivers for *any* percentile claim, and simultaneously mandates SingleStream. Those positions conflict. Open-loop scheduling is necessary for latency-under-offered-load claims; closed-loop SingleStream remains valid for isolated service-time latency. Also, MLPerf’s 23,886-query figure is a suggested starting point for its early-stopping estimator, not a universal required sample size, and early stopping does not replace the 600-second duration. The proposed “600-second-or-statistical-sufficiency” rule is therefore incorrect. See the current [MLPerf inference rules](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mlcommons/inference_policies/master/inference_rules.adoc).

3. **Lifecycle uncertainty is understated rather than closed.**  
   Sardana supports the qualitative proposition that expected inference demand changes optimal training size. It does not make SmolLM2 “inference-optimal,” prove that those comparators have already banked the gain, or directly transfer from pretraining loss to KOT-AI-INDEX capability. Sardana explicitly calls its dollar model simplified and notes failures of extreme-ratio scaling fits. More fundamentally, SYS proposes a crossover using a “per-query resource-vector gap,” but a vector has no crossover until its components are priced or constrained consistently. The design itself refuses a common exchange rate for human hours, GPU hours, latency and energy. P3-D-LIFE still needs billing granularity, utilization/capacity assumptions, maintenance and refresh costs, workload/output-length distributions, discount/time horizon, and sensitivity analysis. [Sardana et al.](https://arxiv.org/html/2401.00448)

## Factual and citation errors

- **Traeger is materially misquoted.** It does not prescribe “at least ten runs.” It says the number should be determined from confidence intervals. Ten runs was the authors’ own experimental configuration. The claimed “surveyed median was 7 runs” is also wrong: seven was the median number of reported system parameters; median run counts were 1–3 by conference. This invalidates the stated literature-backed `≥10` floor in §§6–7. [Primary paper](https://www.fsl.cs.stonybrook.edu/docs/fsbench/fsbench.pdf)

- **MLPerf early stopping is misstated.** The 23,886/24,576 table is suggested guidance for the estimator, not a general query-count requirement. A run must still satisfy its duration condition.

- **“MLPerf LoadGen embodies open-loop discipline” is false as a general statement.** It is true for Server, false for SingleStream and MultiStream.

- **SmolLM2 is not demonstrated to be “inference-optimal.”** Its paper says it was overtrained on about 11T tokens; it does not establish Sardana-optimality for a specified quality, workload, hardware, lifetime demand, or cost model. [SmolLM2 paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.02737)

- **The storage-rent order-of-magnitude claim is wrong.** A tens-of-MB store at roughly $0.09/GiB-month is around $0.001–$0.01/month. Against a $1–$4 GPU-hour, that is roughly 2–4 orders of magnitude lower, not five. Modal also includes 1 TiB/month free, making the relevant marginal price plan-dependent. [Modal pricing](https://modal.com/pricing)

- **“Full RAM residency is always economically optimal” is not licensed by the five-minute rule.** The cited 2017 break-even values are hardware- and price-specific and do not account for cloud RAM billing, capacity constraints, access skew, scale-to-zero, or opportunity cost. It is a hypothesis to evaluate, not a settled conclusion.

- **Cloud/RAPL scope is overgeneralized.** Absence of `/sys/class/powercap` on this EC2 VM was confirmed, but it does not establish absence on “any Modal/cloud container.” The document also says there is no bare-metal host in the pool, then names ARC bare-metal as a candidate.

- **The NVML “unverified” fields are readily verifiable.** NVIDIA documents `nvmlDeviceGetTotalEnergyConsumption` as millijoules since driver reload, supported on fully supported Volta-or-newer devices. Actual availability still needs checking per Modal SKU. [NVIDIA NVML reference](https://docs.nvidia.com/deploy/nvml-api/group__nvmlDeviceQueries.html)

- **The source ledger is not sufficiently auditable for a “verified this session” claim.** Living sources use mutable `master` URLs without commit hashes; entries combine verified and unverified subclaims behind one boolean; most lack page/section/evidence locators. For example, NVML is `verified:false` despite a verified API-existence claim, while Samsi is `verified:true` despite its venue being unverified. Pin versions/commits and split partial claims.

## What is sound

The review correctly rejects TDP as an energy proxy, distinguishes component counters from full-system measurement, requires warm/cold disclosure, recognizes coordinated omission, separates TTFT and TPOT, treats DistServe’s 7.4× as a fixed-SLO scheduling result rather than a general compute win, and does not take a neurosymbolic matched-compute victory from the literature at face value. Its skeptical framing in §10 is one of the strongest parts.

**Bottom line:** sound foundation, not sound final deliverable. Correct the MLPerf/Traeger errors, weaken the Sardana and storage conclusions, make the source ledger reproducible, and—most importantly—resolve the common energy boundary versus W1 admissibility contradiction before closing P3-LR-SYS.